# gen149: inline code debugging — mod_code module.
# Basic checks: missing semicolons, type mismatches, unclosed strings,
# unbalanced braces/parens, unknown functions, language identification.
# The module is grounded in kb/coding.p0; these tests prove the
# behaviour emerges from the KB, not from hardcoded strings.

# --- missing semicolon (declaration without ;) ---
> what is wrong with this code: int x = 5
< Issue found: Missing semicolon at the end of a statement.

# --- missing semicolon (return without ; before }) ---
> what is wrong with this code: int main() { return 0 }
< Issue found: Missing semicolon at the end of a statement.

# --- type mismatch (string assigned to int) ---
> what is wrong with this code: int x = "hello";
< Issue found: Type mismatch: a string is assigned to an int variable. Use char * or char[] for strings.

# --- language identification: C ---
> what language is this code: int main(void) { return 0; }
< This looks like C code.

# --- language identification: Python ---
> what language is this code: def foo(): pass
< This looks like Python code.

# --- fix suggestion (for a missing-semicolon case) ---
> fix this code: int x = "hello"
< Fix: add a semicolon at the end of each statement.

# --- valid code ---
> is this valid C: int x = 5;
< This code looks valid at first glance (basic syntax checks pass).

# --- explain code ---
> explain this code: printf("hello");
< This is a C code snippet. It prints output using printf.
